
Let's do a deep analysis of Method Overriding in Java.

1. What is Method Overriding?

Method Overriding means:

When a child class provides its own implementation of a method that is already defined in the parent class.

It is used for runtime polymorphism.

Example:

class Animal {

    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes sound");
    }

}


class Dog extends Animal {

    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }

}

Here:

Animal has sound()

Dog changes the implementation of sound()

This is overriding.

2. Why do we use Overriding?

Suppose parent has general behavior:

Animal
    sound()

Different animals have different sounds:

Dog → Bark
Cat → Meow
Lion → Roar

So child classes override the same method.

It provides:

Runtime polymorphism
Dynamic method dispatch
Specific implementation
3. Basic Rules of Method Overriding
Rule 1: Parent-child relationship required

Example:

class A {

void show()
{

}

}


class B extends A {

void show()
{

}

}

✔ Valid

But:

class A {

void show()
{

}

}


class B {

void show()
{

}

}

❌ Not overriding

It is just two separate methods.

4. Method Signature Must Be Same

Parent:

class Parent {

void display(int a)
{

}

}

Child:

class Child extends Parent {

void display(int a)
{

}

}

✔ Overriding

Different parameter:

void display(String a)

❌ Not overriding

That becomes overloading.

5. Return Type Rules

Return type must be:

Same
class Parent {

int getValue()
{
return 10;
}

}


class Child extends Parent {


int getValue()
{
return 20;
}

}

✔

Covariant return type allowed

Child can return subclass object.

Example:

class Animal
{

}


class Dog extends Animal
{

}


class Parent {

Animal getAnimal()
{
return new Animal();
}

}


class Child extends Parent {


Dog getAnimal()
{
return new Dog();
}

}

✔ Allowed

Because:

Dog IS-A Animal

6. Access Modifier Rules

Child cannot reduce visibility.

Example:

Parent:

public void show()
{

}

Child:

protected void show()
{

}

❌ Error

Because child is giving less access.

Allowed:

Parent:

protected void show()

Child:

public void show()

✔

Increasing access is allowed.

Access table:

Parent	Child
private	❌
default	default/protected/public
protected	protected/public
public	public
7. Can static methods be overridden?

No.

Static methods belong to class, not object.

Example:

class Parent {

static void show()
{
System.out.println("Parent");
}

}


class Child extends Parent {

static void show()
{
System.out.println("Child");
}

}

This is method hiding, not overriding.

8. Can private methods be overridden?

No.

Example:

class Parent {

private void display()
{

}

}


class Child extends Parent {

private void display()
{

}

}

Not overriding.

Because child cannot see parent's private method.

9. Can final methods be overridden?

No.

Example:

class Parent {

final void show()
{

}

}


class Child extends Parent {

void show()
{

}

}

Error.

final means cannot change.

10. Can constructors be overridden?

No.

Because constructor is not inherited.

Example:

class Parent {

Parent()
{

}

}


class Child extends Parent {

Child()
{

}

}

These are different constructors.

Not overriding.

11. Can main() be overridden?

Technically no.

Because:

public static void main(String args[])

is static.

Static methods are hidden.

12. Using @Override Annotation

Recommended:

class Parent {

void show()
{

}

}


class Child extends Parent {


@Override
void show()
{

}

}

Compiler checks if you are really overriding.

If mistake:

@Override
void sho()
{

}

Compiler error.

13. Runtime Polymorphism

Most important.

Example:

class Animal {

void sound()
{
System.out.println("Animal sound");
}

}


class Dog extends Animal {

void sound()
{
System.out.println("Dog bark");
}

}


public class Main {

public static void main(String args[])
{

Animal a = new Dog();

a.sound();

}

}

Output:

Dog bark

Why?

Reference is Animal.

Object is Dog.

JVM chooses method at runtime.

14. Overloading vs Overriding
Overloading	Overriding
Same class	Parent-child
Same method name	Same method name
Different parameters	Same parameters
Compile time	Runtime
Inheritance not required	Inheritance required
Return type can change	Same/covariant only
Constructors allowed	Constructors not allowed
